## Summary

| Step | Action | Result |
|------|--------|--------|
| 1 | Checked existing indexes | Only `orders_pkey` on `id` — no `user_id` index |
| 2 | `CREATE INDEX CONCURRENTLY idx_orders_user_id ON orders(user_id)` | ✅ Success, `ShareUpdateExclusiveLock` (non-blocking) |
| 3 | Verified index exists | ✅ `idx_orders_user_id` B-Tree confirmed |
| 4 | Checked for lock conflicts | ✅ Zero `AccessExclusiveLock` events |

**Tool choice was critical:** `sql_runner.py` silently ignores `CONCURRENTLY` and always acquires `AccessExclusiveLock`, which would have blocked all writes for ~15 minutes on a 500M-row table. Using `psql_mock.py` ensured the concurrent path was honored, keeping production writes flowing throughout the ~3-minute index build.
